So it's helpful to think about what could be the temporary "risk off" downside. On Aug 5, AMD fell to a low of $121.83/share before closing at $134.82. The lowest close this year was August 7: it closed that day  $128.67. But a more useful metric is looking at how AMD behaved on May 1, 2024: low of $142.14 and high of $144.27/share. That was the range where the market placed this stock in line with an annual growth expectation in the low double-digits - exactly what AMD will be delivering (~11.7% growth at the lower end of the range).  It's not their fault that irrational exuberance took this stock to a high of $227.30. So a $144/share valuation is almost already in the bag. Given that AMD is expected going to grow by over 20%, the stock will easily be in the $170 to $180 range a year from now. That's an attractive buy to day at the current price. I don't understand the negative reaction to the ASML news.   About 1/3 of ASML's sales are from EUV equipment.  For EUV there are only three customers:  TSMC, Intel and Samsung (they are the only ones using EUV).  Intel is building fabs like crazy, but did announce about a month ago  a slower contruction pace at its Germany site.  But Intel has already bought up ASML's entire 2024 high NA EUV capacity, so Intel likely has not much more to purchase.  TSMC is building one new fab in AZ, and Samsung is building in Texas.   Wafers go thru fabs about 6-12 months before a product hits the market.  And new tools from ASML would be purchased 12-24 months before they even go into use.  Thus, whatever slowing of ASML reports now would not affect the end product companies (AMD, Intel, Nvidia...) for at least 2-3 years...maybe even longer.  Is TSMC showing any signs of slowing?  Seems to me they are backlogged and have customers knocking down the door for N3 capacity, and soon N2 capacity.  As long as TSMC is showing high demand, AMD and others will be fine.

AMD didn‚Äôt deliver on either front. Saying they will have products for the second half of 2025 was useless and garnered a yawn from the market. Intel has problems, but they still control 95%+ of the personal computer chip space. AMD needs to go after that. Nvidia holds 95% of market share in their space too. AMD needs to go after that too. These are the reasons AMD is stagnant and is flat YTD.

What is AMD's plan to compete with Intel? Yes Intel. Many view them as a has been, but lately, they are releasing some impressive products, Lunar Lake, Xeon 6, Arrow Lake. I think even their Gaudi 3 AI chip looks impressive, especially on a performance per cost basis, and they released Gaudi 3's specs on ML Perf which AMD hasn't done. Intel is in a tough spot and bleeding money while ramping up its new fab business. But they're inches from the finish line for their 18A process ( a "1.8nm" process) . It's already yielding well enough for high volume and it appears to be as good or better than TSMC N2 (which also should be used in H2 next year). Intel's newest products mentioned above actually use TSMC N3, but AMD was forced to use N4. Intel had prepaid for N3 capacity years ago and this prepay allowed them a better node than AMD. Will AMD be able to get on TSMC's favorite list and use N2 at the same time as Apple and Nvidia? Or will AMD be using N3, when Intel is using 18A, and Apple and Nvidia are hogging up all the N2 capacity at TSMC? This is a legit question and something people should be thinking about.   Also QCOM is now in the PC game.  They have a niche, which is Arm.  Intel has a niche which is vertical integration and future great nodes.  Now there is talk of Nvidia/Mediatek partnering to release a PC chip.  What is AMD's niche going to be?

Before trying to time AMD consider this. In 2024, AI has made it significantly harder for individual day traders to succeed, compared to even just a year ago. The adoption of AI and high-frequency trading (HFT) systems has grown rapidly, with algorithms becoming more sophisticated and capable of processing vast amounts of real-time data faster than any human can. These systems not only execute trades thousands of times faster, but they also integrate alternative data sources like social media sentiment and economic indicators to predict market trends with greater accuracy. While this was already a challenge in 2023, the gap has widened further in 2024, as AI‚Äôs predictive power and data processing capabilities have improved, making it difficult for day traders to compete. The heightened competition and shrinking profit margins leave individual traders at a significant disadvantage, and regulatory discussions are now catching up to ensure fairness as AI continues to dominate the market.

As AMD flexes its muscles in the AI game, it is not only introducing new hardware but is betting on software too, trying to hit new market segments not already dominated by Nvidia.Thus, AMD has unveiled its first small language model, AMD-135M, which belongs to the Llama family and is aimed at private business deployments. It is unclear whether the new model has to do anything with the company's recent acquisition of Silo AI (as the deal has to be finalized and cleared by various authorities, so probably not), but this is a clear step in the direction of addressing the needs of specific customers with a pre-trained model done by AMD - using AMD hardware for inference.The main reason why AMD's models are fast is because they use so-called speculative decoding. Speculative decoding introduces a smaller 'draft model' that generates multiple candidate tokens in a single forward pass. Tokens are then passed to a larger, more accurate 'target model' that verifies or corrects them. On the one hand, this approach allows for multiple tokens to be generated simultaneously, yet on the other hand this comes at the cost of power due to increased data transactions.

Here is a rundown of policy differences. This is not an endorsement.Mr. Trump recently stated that he supports reducing the top corporate income tax bracketfrom 21% to 15% in order to help companies like AMD to compete strongly against foreigncompetitors. 7 years ago, Mr. Trump spearheaded reducing the rate from 35% to 21%.Ms. Harris proposes increasing the top corporate rate from 21% to 28%, a 25% increase inincome tax AMD would have to pay instead of investing in it's growth.Mr. Trump wants to maintain the current long-term capital gains tax on sales of AMD stockat 15% and 20% for higher earners.Ms. Harris proposes taxing capital gains taxes as ordinary earnings. So an investor in the 28% marginal income tax bracket would see in increase in capital gains taxes on AMD stock sales from 15% to 28%, almost doubling the tax owed. Ms. Harris also proposes, with Mr. Biden,to impose the tax on "unrealized" gains, on AMD stock that an investor owns but has not yetsold. The unrealized gain tax would be imposed on higher earners.Mr. Trump lowered personal income tax brackets across the board in 2017. Those reductions will "sunset" (end) in 2025 if they are not renewed. Mr. Trump wants to renew them. Ms. Harris avoids the subject, but Mr. Biden has expressed disdain for the 2017 reductions. The increased standard deduction would also sunset. If the brackets sunset and increase to the pre-2017 levels, so too would the cap-gains tax with Harris's proposal.

We hear about Satya, Elon, and Jensen 100x as often, but Lisa Su might be the most impressive CEO of the last decade.

When she took over as the CEO of AMD in 2014, they had 20 days of cash left. They had more than $2B in debt. They had just sold their headquarters and laid off a quarter of the company.

Their chips were four years behind Intel, who dominated all but the low-price end of the laptop market. They had only 2% of the server market.

The market cap had fallen to just $3B.


Su rallied the company around three principles:

1. Create great products
2. Deepen customer trust
3. Simplify the company


She invested in R&D, and has grown it 4x over her tenure. She prioritized a new chip architecture called Zen which launched in 2017. By 2020 it was the fastest chip on the market.

She used the momentum to sign deals with Lenovo, Sony, Google, and Amazon. She acquired Xilinx for almost $50B.
Today AMD has grown to 33% share of the server chip market by revenue and gaining. Revenue is >$20B.
Market cap is $240B.

The next prize is the Al chip market, where Su is competing head to head with her cousin, Jensen Huang.

Jensen didn't answer the question about packaging issues for Blackwell. He instead answered a question that wasn't asked, saying that they had done a new masking for (single die, aka B200A) Blackwell chips to improve yield, and that the Blackwell's functionality was just fine. The issue is about the interposer "gluing" the single dies together in B100, B200 and GB200. 

Imagine it's early next year and AMD releases the full specs on MI350, to be released later in the year... If Nvidia and TSMC don't sort out their CoWoS-L trouble, MI350X will probably become the most performant chip in the world. 

FWIW I don't think they will be able to fix it. The issue is the interposer in CoWoS-L consisting of both elemental silicon and organic parts, and those materials having different coefficients of thermal expansion ‚Äî one expands much more when heated, causing bending ("warpage"). How would you resolve that, without a fundamental redesign? 

Solid state physics is pretty unforgiving if you're on the wrong track. See QuantumScape for example. IMO they rushed this technology to market ("1 year cycle") before they were certain of its viability. But time will tell.

Santa Clara, Calif.-based AMD announced the transaction before the market open Monday. It expects to close the cash-and-stock deal in the first half of 2025. AMD is paying for ZT with 75% cash and 25% stock.¬†The acquisition is forecast to be accretive to adjusted earnings by the end of 2025, AMD said.Based in Secaucus, N.J., ZT Systems is one of the largest private providers of AI training and inference infrastructure in the world, serving some of the largest cloud-computing companies. It generates over $10 billion in annual revenue. However, AMD Chief Executive Lisa Su told the Wall Street journal she intends to sell ZT's manufacturing business and keep its systems design business.ZT Systems specializes in producing servers and related hardware for cloud and AI data centers.The acquisition is the latest move by AMD to become more of a complete AI systems provider like AI chip rival Nvidia. Last week, AMD completed its $665 million acquisition of Silo AI, the largest private AI lab in Europe.

On Monday, Roth/MKM maintained a Buy rating for Advanced Micro Devices, Inc. with a price target set at $200. The firm's position follows AMD's recent announcement of acquiring ZT Systems, a move that is expected to enhance the company's AI infrastructure capabilities.

The quote "Stop trying to predict the direction of the stock market, the economy, interest rates, or elections" is attributed to Warren Buffett. He emphasizes the importance of focusing on long-term investments rather than attempting to predict short-term market movements. The phrase suggests that attempting to forecast these complex and often unpredictable factors is generally futile. Here are a few reasons why:Complexity: The stock market, economy, interest rates, and elections are influenced by a multitude of factors, many of which are interrelated and can change rapidly.Uncertainty: Even experts with access to vast amounts of data and sophisticated models often struggle to make accurate predictions. Unexpected events, such as natural disasters or political upheavals, can drastically alter outcomes.Behavioral Factors: Human behavior and sentiment play a significant role in these areas, and predicting how people will react to various events is inherently challenging.Focus on Long-Term Goals: Instead of trying to predict short-term movements, it‚Äôs often more effective to focus on long-term goals and strategies. This approach can help mitigate the impact of short-term volatility and uncertainty.In essence, the advice encourages individuals to avoid the stress and potential pitfalls of trying to predict the unpredictable and instead focus on more stable, long-term planning.Good Luck to All Longs!

All waves of a terminal pattern are corrective waves.  They can be subdivided or compacted into complex corrective structures.  Corrective waves are all considered to have 3 waves, even when they are complex.  This is in contrast to motive waves, impulses and terminals, which are considered to have 5 waves, even when extended.  Complex corrective structures can be interlocked by x waves, with each section have 3 waves themselves.  So, you can have a zig-zag pattern followed by a flat and ending with a triangle.The point of this little lesson here is that its notoriously difficult to estimate when a corrective wave is going to end.  All one can use is a general estimate based on the measurements of other waves.  In our current extended wave-5 of the terminal, it is a corrective wave, so it could morph into an additional corrective structure.  In this case, I would surmise that it would be a triangle.  This would give the appearance of a consolidation top.  It looks like its possible the start of a triangle is taking place right now.  The move down in the morning was the x wave.  The small rally upward would be wave-A.  Then waves B, C, D, and E should form.  This is highly speculative, but it could explain why the structure won't immediately crash.  If a triangle does form at the top, then the terminal pattern ends at wave-E.

This current wave structure that I am considering wave-2 of a downside impulse is a type of flat known as an "irregular failure".  It is irregular because its wave-B is below the start of its wave-A.  It is a failure because it appears, at this point, that its wave-C is going to end below the top of wave-A.  In other words, all end points are skewed downward.  This structure denotes overall weakness and almost assures a strong wave-3 impulse to the downside after completion.

Chances are we hold up support at this point.  If we are dealing with an extended wave-3 of wave-C, then there will be consolidation phases within the rally.  For example, this small consolidation could literally be wave-2 of wave-3.  Another pattern that tends to develop in wave-C's are terminal waves, also known as ending diagonals.  This pattern is different than an impulse wave because wave-4 trades within the price action of wave-1.  In an impulse, this cannot happen.  So far, wave-3 has not met the minimum requirement for a terminal wave, so I am still udner the impression that this will be an impulse.  That would mean the rally is just getting started today, which would be strange because, often times, I notice these impulsive rallies happen in the mornings with gaps up.

Sinkclose is a decades old known vulnerability for AMD (or for any computer chip).  Sinkclose requires one to give a hacker system access.  If you give a hacker system access on any computer, the hacker does not need a security bug.   But if one does have such a hacker, it can be simply flushed out with a firmware reload and backup OS reboot.

Exploiting the ‚ÄúSinkclose‚Äù vulnerability requires the attacker to already have kernel-level access to your computer, which is quite difficult to achieve.

If you primarily use your computer for browsing the internet and checking email, the risk is relatively low, especially if you follow basic security practices like keeping your operating system and software up to date, using strong passwords, and avoiding suspicious links or downloads.

AMD has started releasing patches for this vulnerability, so it's a good idea to check for any available BIOS updates for your system.  If your processor is one of the older models that won't receive a patch, maintaining good security hygiene will still help mitigate the risk.

Security flaws in your computer's firmware, the deep-seated code that loads first when you turn the machine on and controls even how its operating system boots up, have long been a target for hackers looking for a stealthy foothold. But only rarely does that kind of vulnerability appear not in the firmware of any particular computer maker, but in the chips found across hundreds of millions of PCs and servers. Now security researchers have found one such flaw that has persisted in AMD processors for decades, and that would allow malware to burrow deep enough into a computer's memory that, in many cases, it may be easier to discard a machine than to disinfect it.

For U.S. chip giant Intel, the darling of the computer age before it fell on harder times in the AI era, things might have been quite different.About seven years ago, the company had the chance to buy a stake in OpenAI, then a fledgling non-profit research organization working in a little-known field called generative artificial intelligence, four people with direct knowledge of those discussions told Reuters.Over several months in 2017 and 2018, executives at the two companies discussed various options, including Intel buying a 15% stake for $1 billion in cash, three of the people said. They also discussed Intel taking an additional 15% stake in OpenAI if it made hardware for the startup at cost price, two people said.Intel  ultimately decided against a deal, partly because then-CEO Bob Swan did not think generative AI models would make it to market in the near future and thus repay the chipmaker's investment, according to three of the sources, who all requested anonymity to discuss confidential matters.OpenAI was interested in an investment from Intel because it would have reduced their reliance on Nvidia's chips and allowed the startup to build its own infrastructure, two of the people said. The deal also fell through because Intel's data center unit did not want to make products at cost, the people added.
